    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Pain and the Brain</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dr Sheila Feit letter on November 23 article about back pain suggests that study that suggests association between brain shrinkage and back pain does not show adequate cause and effect (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Pain and the Downsized Brain'' (Nov. 23): The study described in the article found an association between back pain and brain shrinkage, but it did not prove cause and effect.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Pain and the Downsized Brain'' (Nov. 23): The study described in the article found an association between back pain and brain shrinkage, but it did not prove cause and effect.</p>
        <p>It may be premature to conclude that some back problems can cause permanent changes in brain chemistry if left untreated for too long.</p>
        <p>In fact, the observation that people with chronic pain often ''have impairment in emotional decision making'' raises the possibility that changes in brain chemistry may precede chronic back pain.</p>
        <p>DR. SHEILA FEIT  Syosset, N.Y.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
